<paragraph id="B81F6502FFE6FFAD39B6FCEFFD5FA6DC" blockId="31.[151,1436,798,1471]" pageId="31" pageNumber="132">
<emphasis id="8AD4B910FFE6FFAD39B6FCEFFED5A175" bold="true" box="[151,324,798,823]" pageId="31" pageNumber="132">Redescription.</emphasis>
Length 
<quantity id="7F58C8E7FFE6FFAD3884FCEEFE68A174" box="[421,505,799,823]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.0" pageId="31" pageNumber="132" unit="mm" value="20.0">20 mm</quantity>
. The species is dark chestnut-brown in color with an elongate body. The corporal surface has long setae, reaching their highest density in the thoracic area of the abdomen. Pronotum (
<figureCitation id="209B7987FFE6FFAD3C38FCB3FAE9A119" box="[1305,1400,834,859]" captionStart="FIGURES 110 – 115" captionStartId="32.[151,264,1953,1976]" captionTargetBox="[376,1246,237,1876]" captionTargetId="figure@32.[286,1300,193,1932]" captionTargetPageId="32" captionText="FIGURES 110 – 115. Phyllophaga apolinaria. Pronotum, dorsal view (110), left antenna (111), left metatarsal claw (112), left metatibia (113) male genital capsule, lateral view (114), frontal view (115). Scale: 1 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/219022/files/figure.png" pageId="31" pageNumber="132">
Fig. 
<number id="0E687725FFE6FFAD3C6FFCB2FAE9A119" box="[1358,1400,835,859]" pageId="31" pageNumber="132" value="110.0">110</number>
</figureCitation>
) is wider than it is long, with fine punctures on the dorsal surface, with long, fine setae. Cranial surface is roughly punctate and slightly rounded; the clypeus is not very sharp, with raised and concave margins. Antennae (
<figureCitation id="209B7987FFE6FFAD3C17FC7BFA05A1E1" box="[1334,1428,906,931]" captionStart="FIGURES 110 – 115" captionStartId="32.[151,264,1953,1976]" captionTargetBox="[376,1246,237,1876]" captionTargetId="figure@32.[286,1300,193,1932]" captionTargetPageId="32" captionText="FIGURES 110 – 115. Phyllophaga apolinaria. Pronotum, dorsal view (110), left antenna (111), left metatarsal claw (112), left metatibia (113) male genital capsule, lateral view (114), frontal view (115). Scale: 1 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/219022/files/figure.png" pageId="31" pageNumber="132">
Fig. 
<number id="0E687725FFE6FFAD3C4AFC7AFA05A1E1" box="[1387,1428,907,931]" pageId="31" pageNumber="132" value="111.0">111</number>
</figureCitation>
) have 
<number id="0E687725FFE6FFAD39F2FC5EFF7EA185" box="[211,239,943,967]" pageId="31" pageNumber="132" value="10.0">10</number>
antennomeres with narrow and short antennal clubs. Claws (
<figureCitation id="209B7987FFE6FFAD3A81FC5FFC6EA185" box="[928,1023,942,967]" captionStart="FIGURES 110 – 115" captionStartId="32.[151,264,1953,1976]" captionTargetBox="[376,1246,237,1876]" captionTargetId="figure@32.[286,1300,193,1932]" captionTargetPageId="32" captionText="FIGURES 110 – 115. Phyllophaga apolinaria. Pronotum, dorsal view (110), left antenna (111), left metatarsal claw (112), left metatibia (113) male genital capsule, lateral view (114), frontal view (115). Scale: 1 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/219022/files/figure.png" pageId="31" pageNumber="132">
Fig. 
<number id="0E687725FFE6FFAD3AF4FC5EFC6EA185" box="[981,1023,943,967]" pageId="31" pageNumber="132" value="112.0">112</number>
</figureCitation>
) are cleft with a long, sharp tooth in mid position. Tibiae are flat; protibiae have three lateral teeth, the first two more pronounced and the third one shorter; metatibiae (
<figureCitation id="209B7987FFE6FFAD3859FC07FE46A64D" box="[376,471,1014,1039]" captionStart="FIGURES 110 – 115" captionStartId="32.[151,264,1953,1976]" captionTargetBox="[376,1246,237,1876]" captionTargetId="figure@32.[286,1300,193,1932]" captionTargetPageId="32" captionText="FIGURES 110 – 115. Phyllophaga apolinaria. Pronotum, dorsal view (110), left antenna (111), left metatarsal claw (112), left metatibia (113) male genital capsule, lateral view (114), frontal view (115). Scale: 1 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/219022/files/figure.png" pageId="31" pageNumber="132">
Fig. 
<number id="0E687725FFE6FFAD388CFC06FE46A64D" box="[429,471,1015,1039]" pageId="31" pageNumber="132" value="113.0">113</number>
</figureCitation>
) have medial carinae, and the pair of metatibial spurs are prominent, the outer spur is larger and both are articulated to the tibiae. Male genital capsule (
<figureCitation id="209B7987FFE6FFAD3ABFFBEBFBD2A671" box="[926,1091,1050,1075]" captionStart="FIGURES 110 – 115" captionStartId="32.[151,264,1953,1976]" captionTargetBox="[376,1246,237,1876]" captionTargetId="figure@32.[286,1300,193,1932]" captionTargetPageId="32" captionText="FIGURES 110 – 115. Phyllophaga apolinaria. Pronotum, dorsal view (110), left antenna (111), left metatarsal claw (112), left metatibia (113) male genital capsule, lateral view (114), frontal view (115). Scale: 1 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/219022/files/figure.png" pageId="31" pageNumber="132">
Figs. 
<number id="0E687725FFE6FFAD3AC0FBEBFBD2A671" box="[993,1091,1050,1075]" pageId="31" pageNumber="132" value="114.5" valueMax="115.0" valueMin="114.0">114–115</number>
</figureCitation>
) is strongly sclerotized, long, cylindrical and curved; the short parameres are joined by a membrane, and have a pair of distinctive keels on the outer dorsal margin and a smaller one on the central inner margin; the aedeagus is membranous with minute spines which add a rubbery texture to the entire structure.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="F0BA3689FFE6FFAD39E6FB5BFAA0A7FD" pageId="31" pageNumber="132" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="B81F6502FFE6FFAD39E6FB5BFBD0A710" blockId="31.[151,1436,798,1471]" pageId="31" pageNumber="132">
<emphasis id="8AD4B910FFE6FFAD39E6FB5BFEDEA681" bold="true" box="[199,335,1194,1219]" pageId="31" pageNumber="132">Comments.</emphasis>
The species was originally described from specimens of both sexes obtained by Father Apolinar María in August in &quot;Payne, 
<collectingCountry id="C0B72592FFE6FFAD38EFFB3FFDD3A6A5" box="[462,578,1230,1255]" name="United States of America" pageId="31" pageNumber="132">Columbia</collectingCountry>
&quot;, in Muzo (Boyacá) in July, in “Fusagua” (Cundinamarca) in October, and in “Rio 
<collectingCountry id="C0B72592FFE6FFAD39F2FB03FE81A749" box="[211,272,1266,1291]" name="Chile" pageId="31" pageNumber="132">Chili</collectingCountry>
”. According to Saylor, 
<taxonomicName id="7FA01E81FFE6FFAD3B37FB05FD39A749" box="[534,680,1266,1291]" class="Insecta" family="Melolonthidae" genus="Phyllophaga" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="31" pageNumber="132" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="apolinaria">
<emphasis id="8AD4B910FFE6FFAD3B37FB05FD39A749" box="[534,680,1266,1291]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="132">P. apolinaria</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is similar to 
<emphasis id="8AD4B910FFE6FFAD3A1AFB05FC31A749" box="[827,928,1267,1291]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="132">P. r u f i p e s</emphasis>
Moser and to 
<taxonomicName id="7FA01E81FFE6FFAD3D67FB05FA0DA749" authority="Moser. This" authorityName="Moser. This" box="[1094,1436,1266,1291]" class="Insecta" family="Melolonthidae" genus="Phyllophaga" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="31" pageNumber="132" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="transversicollis">
<emphasis id="8AD4B910FFE6FFAD3D67FB05FA9EA749" box="[1094,1295,1266,1291]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="132">P. transversicollis</emphasis>
Moser. This
</taxonomicName>
study illustrates some of this species’ key features, observed from the 
<typeStatus id="671BDBA0FFE6FFAD3A82FAE7FB99A76D" box="[931,1032,1302,1327]" pageId="31" pageNumber="132">holotype</typeStatus>
, but it is necessary to compare more specimens from other collections in order calculate the proportions of all structures.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="B81F6502FFE6FFAD39E6FAAFFAA0A7FD" blockId="31.[151,1436,798,1471]" pageId="31" pageNumber="132">
The “Diccionario Geográfico de 
<collectingCountry id="C0B72592FFE6FFAD3B1AFAAFFD3DA735" box="[571,684,1374,1399]" name="Colombia" pageId="31" pageNumber="132">Colombia</collectingCountry>
” (Instituto Geográfico Agustín Codazzi 
<number id="0E687725FFE6FFAD3D56FAAFFB21A735" box="[1143,1200,1374,1399]" pageId="31" pageNumber="132" value="1996.0">1996</number>
) has an entry for the city of Fusagasugá (of Chibcha origin, meaning “invisible woman”), located in the Eastern Andes of 
<collectingCountry id="C0B72592FFE6FFAD3C30FA73FAEEA7D9" box="[1297,1407,1410,1435]" name="Colombia" pageId="31" pageNumber="132">Colombia</collectingCountry>
at an altitude of 
<quantity id="7F58C8E7FFE6FFAD3813FA56FE01A7FC" box="[306,400,1447,1471]" metricMagnitude="0" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.4" pageId="31" pageNumber="132" unit="m" value="2.4">2,400 m</quantity>
. The region has a cold climate, with large areas of land dedicated to dairy farming.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
